9(b) Friend Function Example
Aim: To demonstrate how a global friend function can access private and protected members of a class.

Algorithm:

Start the program.
Create a class base with private and protected members.
Declare a global friend function friendFunction.
Use the friend function to access and display the private and protected members.
Stop the program.
Source Code:

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class base {
private:
    int private_variable;
protected:
    int protected_variable;

public:
    base() {
        private_variable = 10;
        protected_variable = 99;
    }
    friend void friendFunction(base &obj);
};

void friendFunction(base &obj) {
    cout << "Private Variable: " << obj.private_variable << endl;
    cout << "Protected Variable: " << obj.protected_variable << endl;
}

int main() {
    base b;
    friendFunction(b);
    return 0;
}
Result:

Private Variable: 10
Protected Variable: 99
